    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:ffb706c2-cadb-452a-bb1d-897c789ffee5",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 59-year-old woman who appears mildly uncomfortable but not acutely ill. She often sits leaning slightly forward with one hand over her upper abdomen, describing a gnawing burning pain in the epigastric area that flares after coffee, late meals, and periods of stress. Over the past several weeks she has noticed intermittent nausea, early satiety, bloating, and sour belching, though she denies dramatic weight loss or severe vomiting. Her face is tired from poor sleep, and she is cautious about eating because rich or spicy foods seem to aggravate her symptoms.\n\nShe works part-time as a bookkeeper for a local hardware supplier, a job that becomes especially busy at the end of each month. Her routine is fairly sedentary during work hours, and she often skips breakfast, relying on coffee to get through the morning. She enjoys gardening, quilting, and meeting two close friends for weekend brunch, though recently she has been avoiding social meals because abdominal discomfort makes her self-conscious. She lives with her husband, helps care for an elderly mother nearby, and says the balancing of responsibilities has increased her stress level.\n\nAt home, {patientName} usually cooks but admits to frequent use of convenience foods on busy days. She drinks 2 to 3 cups of coffee daily and an occasional glass of wine, and she has a long history of taking over-the-counter pain relievers for knee and back aches. She does not smoke. Family members describe her as dependable and stoic, someone who minimizes her own symptoms until they begin to interfere with daily life.\n\nOverall, {patientName} presents as a conscientious, practical woman whose symptoms fit a common outpatient picture of gastritis: upper abdominal burning, postprandial discomfort, nausea, and food-triggered symptom patterns without signs of immediate hemodynamic instability."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:7c8a9565-0475-475a-8ef1-861bbbff3585",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a history of intermittent dyspepsia for several years, usually self-treated with antacids, but her symptoms have become more persistent over the past 2 months. She reports chronic osteoarthritis-related knee pain and has used over-the-counter ibuprofen several times per week, which is a likely contributing factor. Past medical history includes hypertension and mild osteoarthritis. She has not had prior gastrointestinal bleeding or known peptic ulcer disease, and she has never been hospitalized for abdominal complaints.\n\nLifestyle factors include irregular meals, frequent coffee intake, occasional alcohol use, and elevated psychosocial stress related to work deadlines and caregiving responsibilities. She denies tobacco use. She had a cholecystectomy years ago and recovered without complication. There is no known history of liver disease, pancreatitis, or inflammatory bowel disease. She seeks evaluation now because the epigastric pain and nausea are interfering with appetite, sleep, and social meals."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}